":"1217","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1189":"1189","1210":"1210","Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England":"Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Of Wiloughby, Lincolnshire England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Willoughby, Lincolnshire, , England":"Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1217–3 Feb 1257":"circa 1217–3 februari 1257","1210–1257":"1210–1257","1217–1257":"1217–1257","1210–1245":"1210–1245","1240–1300":"1240–1300","1170–1225":"1170–1225","–1220":"–1220","3 Feb 1257":"3 februari 1257","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1170":"1170","Abt 1217":"circa 1217","1217":"1217","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1189":"1189","1210":"1210","Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England":"Willoughby, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Of Wiloughby, Lincolnshire England":"Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Willoughby, Lincolnshire, , England":"Willoughby, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1217–3 Feb 1257":"about 1217–3 February 1257","1210–1257":"1210–1257","1217–1257":"1217–1257","1210–1245":"1210–1245","1240–1300":"1240–1300","1170–1225":"1170–1225","–1220":"–1220","3 Feb 1257":"3 February 1257","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1170":"1170","Abt 1217":"about 1217","1217":"1217","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1189":"1189","1210":"1210","Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England":"Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Of Wiloughby, Lincolnshire England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Willoughby, Lincolnshire, , England":"Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Willoughby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Willoughby, for example in Leicestershire, Lincolnshire, Nottinghamshire, and Warwickshire. They are named from an Old English +<i>wilig</i> ‘willow’ + Old Norse <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Wilby","meanings":["habitational name from any of the places called Wilby, in Suffolk, Norfolk, and Northamptonshire. The first placename is probably named from an Old English <i>wilig</i> ‘willow’ + Old English <i>bēag</i> ‘circle, ring’; the Norfolk placename derives from Old English <i>wilig</i> + <i>bēag</i> or Old Norse <i>bý</i> ‘farmstead, village’; the Northamptonshire placename derives from the Old Norse personal name <i>Vili</i> + <i>bý</i>.","Redmonds has demonstrated that in the parish of Hipperholme, and subsequently elsewhere in Yorkshire, <i>Wilby</i> occurs as a variant of   Willoughby  .","English:"]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":7,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Willoughby was born about 1217, in Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England as the son of Sir William de Willoughby x and Maud Fulletby. He married Margaret Orreby in 1230, in Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 3 February 1257, in Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 41."},"et":{"Abt 1217–3 Feb 1257":"umbes 1217–3. veebruar 1257","1210–1257":"1210–1257","1217–1257":"1217–1257","1210–1245":"1210–1245","1240–1300":"1240–1300","1170–1225":"1170–1225","–1220":"–1220","3 Feb 1257":"3. veebruar 1257","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1240":"1240","1170":"1170","Abt 1217":"umbes 1217","1217":"1217","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1245":"1245","1300":"1300","1189":"1189","1210":"1210","Willoughby, Lincolnshire, England":"Willoughby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of Wiloughby, Lincolnshire England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Willoughby, Lincolnshire, , England":"Willoughby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1217–3 Feb 1257":"noin 1217–3. helmikuuta 1257","1210–1257":"1210–1257","1217–1257":"1217–1257","1210–1245":"1210–1245","1240–1300":"1240–1300","1170–1225":"1170–1225","–1220":"–1220","3 Feb 1257":"3. h